The paper discusses the ethical impacts of pretrained deep learning models, which are commonly used in artificial intelligence practice. This suggests that the paper belongs to the cs.AI sub-category. The paper also discusses the performative effect of pretrained models on society, which relates to the cs.CY sub-category that deals with the social and cultural aspects of computing. The discussion of biases in pretrained models suggests that the paper may also belong to the cs.CR sub-category that deals with security and privacy. The paper also discusses the development and comparison of pretrained models, which relates to the cs.LG sub-category that deals with machine learning. Finally, the paper discusses how users may use pretrained models in malicious ways, which relates to the cs.SI sub-category that deals with social and information networks.
